Ann Arbor Climate Extremes

Kiera Matiska

2023-04-15

Read in Data

climate_clean <- read_csv(here("data", "A2_climate_data.csv")) %>% 
  clean_names()

climate <- climate_clean %>% 
  mutate(date = ymd(date)) %>% 
  mutate(year = substr(date, 1, 4)) %>% 
  mutate(month = substr(date, 6, 7)) %>% 
  mutate(day = substr(date, 9, 10)) %>% 
  mutate(season = case_when(
    month == "01" ~ "winter",
    month == "02" ~ "winter",
    month == "03" ~ "winter",
    month == "04" ~ "spring",
    month == "05" ~ "spring",
    month == "06" ~ "spring",
    month == "07" ~ "summer",
    month == "08" ~ "summer",
    month == "09" ~ "summer",
    month == "10" ~ "fall",
    month == "11" ~ "fall",
    month == "12" ~ "fall"
  ))

The temperature range in Ann Arbor, MI is normally 17°F to 84°F. I am going to use those two numbers, anything below the low and above the high, for my extremes analysis. Any day that has precipitation - including both rain or snow - above 1.25” is likely to have a large flood event.

Extreme Metrics

Temperature

Extreme Cold Days

climate$freeze <- ifelse(climate$tmin <= 17, 1, 0)

clim_fr_sum <- climate %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(freeze_days = sum(freeze)) %>% 
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year))

ggplot(data = clim_fr_sum,
       aes(x = year, y = freeze_days)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x,
              color = "black",
              method = "lm",
              se = FALSE)

freeze_lm <- lm(freeze_days ~ year, data = clim_fr_sum)

The y-intercept value stands at 314.54 days. The slope for freeze days per year is -0.138 and is statistically significant with a p-value of 5.82e-06.

Extreme Hot Days

climate$heat <- ifelse(climate$tmax >= 84, 1, 0)

clim_ht_sum <- climate %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(heat_days = sum(heat)) %>% 
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year))

ggplot(data = clim_ht_sum, 
       aes(x = year, y = heat_days)) +
  geom_point(color = "red") +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x,
              color = "black",
              method = "lm",
              se = FALSE)

heat_lm <- lm(heat_days ~ year, data = clim_ht_sum)

The y-intercept value stands at -59.28 days. The slope for heat days per year is 0.053 and is not statistically significant with a p-value of 0.14.

Precipitation

climate$precip <- ifelse(climate$all_prcp >= 1.25, 1, 0)

clim_prcp_sum <- climate %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarize(high_precip_days = sum(precip)) %>% 
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year))

ggplot(data = clim_prcp_sum, 
       aes(x = year, y = high_precip_days)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue") +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x,
              color = "black",
              method = "lm",
              se = FALSE)

all_precip_lm <- lm(high_precip_days ~ year, data = clim_prcp_sum)

The y-intercept value stands at -140.31 days. The slope for extreme precipitation days per year is 0.079 and is statistically significant with a p-value of 2.36e-10.
